Identify SQL queries. Locate all SQL queries throughout your application. 


          Identify the parameters in each SQL query. After locating all SQL queries, identify the parameters in each query. Understand the format and type of each parameter's data.


            Use prepared statements for SQL queries. Substitute the parameters in SQL queries with question marks ("?"). The basic steps for writing a prepared statement are: get a database handle, call the prepare function to make the prepared statement, use the bindParam function to bind prepared statement parameters to variables, load data into the variables, and call the execute function to execute the prepared statement. For examples and more information about writing prepared statements in PHP, please see the link at the bottom of this article. One example of a prepared statement is:
          // Create the prepared statement. Notice the ?, which defines the parameter.$preparedStatement = $databaseHandle->prepare("SELECT * FROM USERS WHERE Name =  ?");// Bind a variable to the parameter.$preparedStatement->bindParam(1, $name);// Load data into the parameter.$name = "Joe";// Execute the prepared statement.$preparedStatement->execute();
